Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.07,0:00:07.29,English,,0,0,0,,Greetings, and welcome to LGR Oddware,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.29,0:00:12.84,English,,0,0,0,,where we're taking a look at hardware and software that is odd, forgotten, and obsolete,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.84,0:00:17.28,English,,0,0,0,,like this thing here, the Yamaha DiscT@2ing system,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.28,0:00:21.67,English,,0,0,0,,or rather the drive that allowed it to happen in the early 2000s.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:21.67,0:00:23.88,English,,0,0,0,,And yeah it's kind of just a CD-RW,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.88,0:00:28.55,English,,0,0,0,,but its whole gimmick was the fact that you could burn,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.55,0:00:33.55,English,,0,0,0,,or ink, "tattoos" directly onto your CD-R media,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.78,0:00:37.70,English,,0,0,0,,not the label side, the data side.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.70,0:00:38.65,English,,0,0,0,,Let's check it out.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.82,0:00:45.01,English,,0,0,0,,All right, so let's take a closer look at the Yamaha CRW-F1,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.01,0:00:49.66,English,,0,0,0,,or more precisely the external SCSI version known as the F1SX.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.66,0:00:53.47,English,,0,0,0,,Yamaha made multiple models, external and internal,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.47,0:00:55.01,English,,0,0,0,,many of which cost less than this one,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.01,0:01:00.01,English,,0,0,0,,but they all had the DiscT@2 laser labeling system built in.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.58,0:01:03.55,English,,0,0,0,,"Draw images on your discs." Mmm~
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.55,0:01:08.55,English,,0,0,0,,And this model cost a whopping $279.99.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.73,0:01:10.02,English,,0,0,0,,Internal versions cost less,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.02,0:01:14.18,English,,0,0,0,,but on average they were all more expensive than the other CD-RW options
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.18,0:01:18.07,English,,0,0,0,,when it released on July 15th, 2002.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.07,0:01:20.97,English,,0,0,0,,As if I really needed to say 2002, though.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.97,0:01:26.75,English,,0,0,0,,I mean, just take one look at that '@' sign in the name there and, yeah, 2002 indeed.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.75,0:01:29.81,English,,0,0,0,,Now overall, this really is just a CD-RW.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.81,0:01:32.93,English,,0,0,0,,I mean, it had a lotta great features for its time,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.93,0:01:35.82,English,,0,0,0,,but of course the standout was the 'T@2ing' ability,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.82,0:01:42.17,English,,0,0,0,,which Yamaha hailed as the first CD-RW drive that could be used for on-disc labeling.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.17,0:01:45.99,English,,0,0,0,,And it predates LightScribe by about two years.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.99,0:01:48.07,English,,0,0,0,,There are some important distinctions between them, though,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.07,0:01:52.04,English,,0,0,0,,because with LightScribe you had to have LightScribe media
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.04,0:01:56.50,English,,0,0,0,,and it printed on the label side, as you'd expect.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.50,0:02:01.64,English,,0,0,0,,But with DiscT@2ing, it's on the data side of the disc where it puts the label,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.64,0:02:06.97,English,,0,0,0,,which, yes, that means it limits your data storage capability on your CD-R.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.97,0:02:08.98,English,,0,0,0,,But Yamaha claimed that most users
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.98,0:02:12.36,English,,0,0,0,,only recorded about 350 megabytes onto CD-R anyway,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.36,0:02:14.28,English,,0,0,0,,so it's fine, don't worry about it.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.28,0:02:17.49,English,,0,0,0,,They were happy to brag about all of its cool applications
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.49,0:02:21.19,English,,0,0,0,,in its "Burnin' Love" press release, saying that you could write:
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.19,0:02:24.40,English,,0,0,0,,"Graphic images which are practically tattooed on,"
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.40,0:02:27.82,English,,0,0,0,,and, "This enables the user to write a practical memo
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.82,0:02:34.06,English,,0,0,0,,such as a date, index, logo or picture on the unused area of the disc."
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.06,0:02:38.31,English,,0,0,0,,And yeah, the other big distinction is that you can use any disc you want.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.31,0:02:42.24,English,,0,0,0,,As long as it's a CD-R, DiscT@2ing works.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.24,0:02:48.66,English,,0,0,0,,Though Yamaha did sell their own DiscT@2 media as well with blue AZO dye.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.66,0:02:52.48,English,,0,0,0,,Eh, so that was a thing, but yeah, you can use whatever CD-Rs you want.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.48,0:02:56.06,English,,0,0,0,,Now, the way this works, according to the old coverage that I found of this,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.06,0:03:02.25,English,,0,0,0,,is that you make a disc design and then that is then turned by the software into a bitmap
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.25,0:03:05.94,English,,0,0,0,,and converted from Cartesian to polar coordinates
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.94,0:03:10.39,English,,0,0,0,,before being written to the CRW-F1's 8-megabyte cache.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.39,0:03:12.23,English,,0,0,0,,And then the data is transferred sequentially
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.23,0:03:16.51,English,,0,0,0,,from the cache to the YDC132-V controller chip,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.51,0:03:19.57,English,,0,0,0,,something Yamaha was very proud of, it was in all the marketing,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.57,0:03:24.67,English,,0,0,0,,and then it converts the greyscale information from the image into a pixel pattern
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.67,0:03:29.19,English,,0,0,0,,with a minimum pixel size, or pit size, of .1 millimeter.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.19,0:03:31.60,English,,0,0,0,,And of course this also meant that the disc's
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.60,0:03:35.30,English,,0,0,0,,table of contents had to be written before the label,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.30,0:03:37.17,English,,0,0,0,,otherwise there'd be problems with drives
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.17,0:03:40.62,English,,0,0,0,,trying to read the label with its tiny little pits as data
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.62,0:03:43.35,English,,0,0,0,,and then screwing things up, and you don't want that.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.35,0:03:46.33,English,,0,0,0,,And as soon as I heard about thing, the obvious question is,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.33,0:03:48.91,English,,0,0,0,,"What in the world are the results like?"
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.91,0:03:52.83,English,,0,0,0,,because Yamaha always showed these higher-contrast images
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.83,0:03:56.18,English,,0,0,0,,on blue CD-Rs and press releases and ads and whatnot
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.18,0:03:59.50,English,,0,0,0,,and it all seemed very controlled, made me a little skeptical.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.50,0:04:02.48,English,,0,0,0,,And the overall consensus from reviewers at the time
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.48,0:04:07.34,English,,0,0,0,,seems to be that DiscT@2ing was fun but not very useful.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.34,0:04:09.93,English,,0,0,0,,It was praised largely for its other features.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.93,0:04:11.01,English,,0,0,0,,You know, the drive itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.01,0:04:13.55,English,,0,0,0,,It had very fast CD-RW writing,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.55,0:04:14.96,English,,0,0,0,,a large eight-megabyte buffer,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.96,0:04:17.61,English,,0,0,0,,and a whole buncha really cool audio recording stuff,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.61,0:04:20.21,English,,0,0,0,,but it was deemed to not really be worth
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.21,0:04:23.88,English,,0,0,0,,the relatively high asking price compared to its competitors.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.88,0:04:26.30,English,,0,0,0,,So most reviewers just said, "Wait for a sale."
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.30,0:04:28.38,English,,0,0,0,,And, well, it didn't last very long.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:28.38,0:04:31.23,English,,0,0,0,,Yamaha actually stopped making the drives in 2003,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.23,0:04:34.17,English,,0,0,0,,so this barely lasted a year on the market
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.17,0:04:38.48,English,,0,0,0,,before having the plug pulled and DiscT@2ing was all but forgotten about,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.48,0:04:41.76,English,,0,0,0,,with a notable exception, because the tech kind of evolved
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.76,0:04:45.63,English,,0,0,0,,and it eventually resulted in Labelflash in 2005,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.63,0:04:48.83,English,,0,0,0,,which was a collaboration between Yamaha and Fujifilm.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.83,0:04:50.19,English,,0,0,0,,And while that was very similar
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.19,0:04:54.55,English,,0,0,0,,in that you could print labels on the data side of your DVD,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.55,0:04:56.83,English,,0,0,0,,it was only DVDs and not CDs
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.83,0:05:02.17,English,,0,0,0,,and it required a proprietary DVD-R media supporting Labelflash.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.17,0:05:05.80,English,,0,0,0,,And even more similar than that was Lite-On's LabelTag,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.80,0:05:09.83,English,,0,0,0,,although it's not really related as far as I can tell in terms of the tech.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.83,0:05:13.85,English,,0,0,0,,That arrived in 2010 and it didn't need proprietary discs,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.85,0:05:21.13,English,,0,0,0,,much like DiscT@2, but again, it only worked on DVD recordable media, not CD-Rs.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.13,0:05:26.50,English,,0,0,0,,Also of note is that despite the fact that DiscT@2 was dropped by Yamaha in 2003,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.50,0:05:33.72,English,,0,0,0,,NEC and Pioneer also built drives with DiscT@2 support until 2010, technically.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.72,0:05:38.84,English,,0,0,0,,More so it was included by default because of the aforementioned Labelflash
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.84,0:05:45.03,English,,0,0,0,,and Labelflash DVD burners retained DiscT@2 compatibility, just kind of as a given.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.03,0:05:47.48,English,,0,0,0,,Now, like I said, there were multiple versions of this.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.48,0:05:49.86,English,,0,0,0,,This just happens to be the external SCSI version,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.86,0:05:54.55,English,,0,0,0,,but there was also an external USB 2.0 model, and a Firewire one
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.55,0:06:01.14,English,,0,0,0,,and internal drives fitting in 5.25" drive bays over IDE in either white or black.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.14,0:06:04.42,English,,0,0,0,,And, you know, any of these drives would've been pretty awesome to have at the time,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.42,0:06:06.57,English,,0,0,0,,just even without the DiscT@2ing.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.57,0:06:07.93,English,,0,0,0,,It's other capabilities?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.93,0:06:09.84,English,,0,0,0,,That's not why it's on "Oddware" here,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.84,0:06:14.15,English,,0,0,0,,because, uh, the other stuff is pretty great, not odd at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.15,0:06:16.95,English,,0,0,0,,It's got a lotta great specs. Which I'm not interested in!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.95,0:06:20.73,English,,0,0,0,,We're just gonna take a look at the DiscT@2ing features here,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.73,0:06:22.62,English,,0,0,0,,so let's get it unboxed and set up.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.38,0:06:30.10,English,,0,0,0,,So you can see from the package contents what was supposed to be in here originally,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.10,0:06:33.78,English,,0,0,0,,but unfortunately it's not quite complete in this case.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.78,0:06:35.94,English,,0,0,0,,But that's fine, it's still got what we need,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.94,0:06:40.94,English,,0,0,0,,including the AC adapter, 12-volt, 3-amp, 36 watts.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.04,0:06:44.24,English,,0,0,0,,And the software, which, really, this is all we need
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.24,0:06:47.28,English,,0,0,0,,since we're using the Windows version here.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.28,0:06:51.87,English,,0,0,0,,It also came with some Mac software with a different program for burning stuff, Toast 5.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.87,0:06:55.54,English,,0,0,0,,And a quick start guide, also this is also for the Macintosh.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.54,0:06:59.26,English,,0,0,0,,There's no Windows one. It was lost by the previous owner.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.26,0:07:02.99,English,,0,0,0,,Yeah, and then you got the drive itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.99,0:07:04.84,English,,0,0,0,,And there we go.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.84,0:07:07.70,English,,0,0,0,,Pretty standard-lookin' external CD-RW drive
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.70,0:07:10.78,English,,0,0,0,,with that nice Yamaha logo debossed into the top.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.78,0:07:13.74,English,,0,0,0,,Pretty groovy sides goin' on here.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.74,0:07:16.58,English,,0,0,0,,And around back, SCSI connections,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.58,0:07:19.07,English,,0,0,0,,including some termination points,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.07,0:07:21.72,English,,0,0,0,,RCA line out for CD audio,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.72,0:07:23.68,English,,0,0,0,,power switch and port, that kinda thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.68,0:07:28.22,English,,0,0,0,,But yeah, it's high time to get this plugged into a Windows XP PC
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.22,0:07:32.83,English,,0,0,0,,and try our hand at inking up some CD-Rs with DiscT@2 :-)
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.95,0:07:44.80,English,,0,0,0,,All right, so I've got the Yamaha drive plugged in to the Windows XP PC going here,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.80,0:07:47.04,English,,0,0,0,,and that goes straight into SCSI.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.04,0:07:49.24,English,,0,0,0,,And in terms of setup it's incredibly simple.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.24,0:07:52.17,English,,0,0,0,,I've already done it. It pretty much just does it itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.17,0:07:56.93,English,,0,0,0,,The Adaptec SCSI controller card that's in this system just goes ahead and finds it.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.93,0:08:01.46,English,,0,0,0,,And it's that right there, it sees it as a CRW-F1S.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.46,0:08:07.23,English,,0,0,0,,And at this point it just looks like any other CD-RW that you have on Windows XP.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.23,0:08:09.21,English,,0,0,0,,So it is ready to go.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.21,0:08:13.80,English,,0,0,0,,And in terms of the software, that's also a little simpler than I thought it might be.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.78,0:08:20.06,English,,0,0,0,,Yeah, that thing whirring to life has got some noise.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.06,0:08:21.52,English,,0,0,0,,Anyway, yeah, this is it.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.52,0:08:28.92,English,,0,0,0,,It's just a Nero 5 installation with regular versions of Nero and NCD packet writing,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.92,0:08:32.90,English,,0,0,0,,so you just install it like you normally would Nero Burning ROM.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.90,0:08:35.14,English,,0,0,0,,No special drivers or Yamaha software
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.14,0:08:39.54,English,,0,0,0,,or anything outside of the actual burning software itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.54,0:08:44.27,English,,0,0,0,,So we'll go ahead and grab ourselves a CD-R.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.27,0:08:47.27,English,,0,0,0,,I got a fresh pack here.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.27,0:08:49.61,English,,0,0,0,,'Bout ready to boot up some LimeWire and get us some music.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.61,0:08:50.44,English,,0,0,0,,No, don't do that.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.44,0:08:51.93,English,,0,0,0,,That's a terrible idea these days.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.83,0:08:55.16,English,,0,0,0,,Actually, it was a terrible idea back in the day, too.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.16,0:08:56.98,English,,0,0,0,,Use virus scanners, folks.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.98,0:09:03.17,English,,0,0,0,,Anyway, here once again it just shows up like a normal recordable CD drive in Windows XP,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.17,0:09:05.53,English,,0,0,0,,but we're gonna go ahead and open Burning ROM.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.53,0:09:09.98,English,,0,0,0,,And you might've seen really briefly there there's a little, slight different thing here.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.98,0:09:14.70,English,,0,0,0,,"Version 5.5.8.19 Yamaha."
Dialogue: 0,0:09:14.70,0:09:21.73,English,,0,0,0,,So this is actually a slightly modified or augmented version of Nero 5, which is great.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.73,0:09:26.04,English,,0,0,0,,I mean, honestly, I still use a later version of Nero for burning certain types of CDs,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.04,0:09:28.73,English,,0,0,0,,so really familiar and awesome to use.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.73,0:09:29.88,English,,0,0,0,,And everything looks the same
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.88,0:09:33.80,English,,0,0,0,,except for when you get to this Miscellaneous tab whenever you're burning something.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.80,0:09:38.68,English,,0,0,0,,You have Burn DiscT@2 as an option.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.68,0:09:44.43,English,,0,0,0,,So if you do that and click Create, it'll open this T@2 Editor.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.43,0:09:48.98,English,,0,0,0,,And this is where you take care of doin' T@2s.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.98,0:09:54.83,English,,0,0,0,,And it works pretty much like any other editor I've ever used for creating disc labels.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.83,0:09:56.13,English,,0,0,0,,I don't know what I'm creating here.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.13,0:09:58.33,English,,0,0,0,,Let's put some text onto it.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.33,0:10:01.77,English,,0,0,0,,So we have a Text Box tool. An Artistic Text tool?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.53,0:10:08.35,English,,0,0,0,,So, of course, we can change the size.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.35,0:10:12.16,English,,0,0,0,,We can change the font to whatever.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.16,0:10:15.38,English,,0,0,0,,I mean, we can go with Comic Sans if we want.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.38,0:10:16.99,English,,0,0,0,,Got a couple of different text options.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.99,0:10:20.02,English,,0,0,0,,We got Read-only, which just makes it, so you can't edit the text,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.02,0:10:22.70,English,,0,0,0,,and then Bent, which changes it...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.70,0:10:23.90,English,,0,0,0,,Let's see.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.90,0:10:27.78,English,,0,0,0,,Yeah, it just sorta wraps around the CD.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:27.78,0:10:30.64,English,,0,0,0,,Then you can do that.
